      FTX vs. Grayscale
   =20
 =20

The Grayscale Bitcoin Trust is a pot that contains Bitcoins. Shares of the =
trust =E2=80=94 each=C2=A0representing a share of ownership of the Bitcoins=
 in the pot =E2=80=94=C2=A0trade publicly on OTC Markets like shares of sto=
ck. If you have some Bitcoins and want shares of the pot, you can go to Gra=
yscale Investments LLC =E2=80=94=C2=A0which runs the trust =E2=80=94=C2=A0a=
nd give them your Bitcoins, and they will give you back shares in the pot. =
If you have shares of the pot and you want some Bitcoins, however, you=C2=
=A0can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0go to Grayscale and ask for the Bitcoins back. The po=
t is one-way. Bitcoins can come in, but they cannot leave.
This is suboptimal product design for customers, but it is very very good p=
roduct design=C2=A0for Grayscale. As an asset manager, it is just good busi=
ness to run=C2=A0a pot of money that can increase (when people put in Bitco=
ins)=C2=A0but not decrease (they can=E2=80=99t take them out).
  [1]
=C2=A0Grayscale has=C2=A0got all these Bitcoins in the pot =E2=80=94  about=
 $14 billion worth =E2=80=94 and, as the manager=C2=A0of the pot, it gets=
=C2=A0to charge fees on the money in the pot. The fee is 2% per year, so Gr=
ayscale collects about $280 million a year for sitting on its giant pot of =
Bitcoin. Grayscale also has a  Grayscale Ethereum Trust, the same idea but =
for Ether; that has $4.7 billion of Ether in the pot and a 2.5% annual fee.
These trusts became a famous widowmaker trade in crypto; name any high-prof=
ile 2022 crypto bankruptcy, and you will probably find a reference to Grays=
cale in its bankruptcy filings. The situation is that early on (the Graysca=
le Bitcoin Trust was created in 2013), owning Bitcoin directly was a pretty=
 off-putting proposition for a lot of people =E2=80=94=C2=A0you had to be f=
airly technically savvy to hold Bitcoin directly, or you had to own it on a=
n exchange that would probably rob you or get hacked =E2=80=94=C2=A0so owni=
ng shares in a pot of Bitcoin in your brokerage account was pretty attracti=
ve. Ordinary investors who wanted Bitcoin exposure without a lot of hassle =
wanted to buy Grayscale shares, so those shares traded at a premium: If the=
 pot had $12 of Bitcoin per share, the shares might trade at $15.
So big crypto trading firms like Three Arrows Capital and Alameda Research =
would do the Grayscale arbitrage trade: You buy $12 million of Bitcoin, you=
 deliver it to Grayscale, you get back 1 million shares of the Grayscale Bi=
tcoin Trust and you sell them for $15 million, collecting the premium. It w=
asn=E2=80=99t quite as easy as that, though; for securities-law reasons, yo=
u had to wait a while (originally a year, more recently six months) between=
 when you got the shares and when you sold them. If the price of Bitcoin we=
nt down in that time, you=E2=80=99d lose money. An alternative trade=C2=A0w=
as to=C2=A0borrow=C2=A0$12 million of Bitcoin, deliver them to Grayscale, g=
et shares, wait and sell them.=C2=A0Then you had no exposure to Bitcoin pri=
ces; if the price of Bitcoin fell by 50%, then you=E2=80=99d only get $7.5 =
million for your Grayscale shares but you=E2=80=99d only have to pay $6 mil=
lion to buy back the Bitcoins you borrowed.
So the arbitrage firms   did this trade as a very=C2=A0levered=C2=A0bet, bo=
rrowing a bunch of dollars or Bitcoins to do the trade and collect the Gray=
scale premium. The results were:=C2=A0
=09lots of Bitcoin got locked up in Grayscale=E2=80=99s pot;=09lots of Gray=
scale Bitcoin Trust shares were created;=09lots of big crypto arbitrage fir=
ms had huge levered bets on the Grayscale premium.

Over time, it became easier for ordinary people to hold Bitcoin in other wa=
ys. Crypto exchanges (mostly) became a bit safer and less likely to rob you=
; crypto self-custody became a bit easier. Regular retail brokerages got in=
to the crypto business. Bitcoin futures started trading on regular futures =
exchanges, and=C2=A0Bitcoin futures exchange-traded funds=C2=A0were approve=
d. The demand for Grayscale shares waned, but the supply grew as all these =
arbitrage firms were doing the Grayscale trade. The results were:
=09By 2020, the Grayscale premium collapsed and became negative: Now Graysc=
ale Bitcoin Trust shares trade at a=C2=A0discount=C2=A0to the value of the =
Bitcoin in the pot;=09Three Arrows and Alameda, which had made levered bets=
 on the premium,=C2=A0went bankrupt, as did lots of the platforms (FTX, Voy=
ager, Celsius, etc.) that were lending them money or Bitcoins to do the tra=
de
  [2]
;=09People stopped doing the Grayscale arbitrage trade: Since Grayscale sha=
res were now trading at a discount, there was no reason to give Grayscale B=
itcoins to get back shares, and no one has done so for two years; but=09The=
 Bitcoins that were=C2=A0already=C2=A0in Grayscale=E2=80=99s pot =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0$14 billion at current prices =E2=80=94=C2=A0stayed there. No Bitcoin=
s are coming in anymore, but none are going out either.

As of yesterday, the closing price of a  Grayscale Bitcoin Trust share was =
$11.77, versus a net asset value per share of $20.33, a discount of 42%. Th=
e Ethereum Trust discount is 55%.
Now, to be fair to Grayscale:=C2=A0I said that this product design =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0Bitcoins can come into the pot but never come out =E2=80=94=C2=A0i=
s bad for customers but good for Grayscale, but in fact Grayscale doesn=E2=
=80=99t like this product design either. Grayscale has been asking the US S=
ecurities and Exchange Commission for years to approve the conversion of th=
e trust into an exchange-traded fund. If the trust becomes an ETF, then it =
will have the same creation/redemption mechanics as most other ETFs: Arbitr=
ageurs can hand Grayscale Bitcoins, get back shares, and sell them immediat=
ely; or they can hand Grayscale shares, get back Bitcoins, and sell them. T=
hat should lead to a price for the shares that closely tracks the net asset=
 value of the pot of Bitcoins: If the shares trade at a premium, arbitrageu=
rs will deliver Bitcoin and get shares to sell, but if they trade at a disc=
ount arbitrageurs will buy shares to deliver to get back Bitcoin.=C2=A0At t=
oday=E2=80=99s prices, closing the discount=C2=A0would create about $6 bill=
ion of value in the Bitcoin trust and about $2.6 billion of value for the E=
thereum one.
It might also lead to =E2=80=A6=C2=A0huge inflows into the trust? Huge outf=
lows? Could go either way? In its early years, Grayscale got huge inflows b=
ecause it was a better-than-the-alternatives way to hold crypto, but right =
now it seems like a pretty terrible way to hold crypto, what with the disco=
