<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">FTX vs. Grayscale</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Grayscale Bitcoin Trust is a pot that cont=
ains Bitcoins. Shares of the trust =E2=80=94 each=C2=A0representing a share=
 of ownership of the Bitcoins in the pot =E2=80=94=C2=A0trade publicly on O=
TC Markets like shares of stock. If you have some Bitcoins and want shares =
of the pot, you can go to Grayscale Investments LLC =E2=80=94=C2=A0which ru=
ns the trust =E2=80=94=C2=A0and give them your Bitcoins, and they will give=
 you back shares in the pot. If you have shares of the pot and you want som=
e Bitcoins, however, you=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>go to Grayscale a=
nd ask for the Bitcoins back. The pot is one-way. Bitcoins can come in, but=
 they cannot leave.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is suboptimal product design for customer=
s, but it is very very good product design=C2=A0<em>for Grayscale</em>. As =
an asset manager, it is just good business to run=C2=A0a pot of money that =
can increase (when people put in Bitcoins)=C2=A0but not decrease (they can=
=E2=80=99t take them out).<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importan=
t; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Grayscale has=C2=A0got all these Bitcoins in the pot =E2=80=94 <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30759013.257411/aHR0=
cHM6Ly9ncmF5c2NhbGUuY29tL3Byb2R1Y3RzL2dyYXlzY2FsZS1iaXRjb2luLXRydXN0Lw/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0d6af257" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> about $14 billion worth</a> =E2=80=
=94 and, as the manager=C2=A0of the pot, it gets=C2=A0to charge fees on the=
 money in the pot. The fee is 2% per year, so Grayscale collects about $280=
 million a year for sitting on its giant pot of Bitcoin. Grayscale also has=
 a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30759013.257411=
/aHR0cHM6Ly9ncmF5c2NhbGUuY29tL3Byb2R1Y3RzL2dyYXlzY2FsZS1ldGhlcmV1bS10cnVzdC=
8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBde87abfd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Grayscale Ethereum Trust</a>,=
 the same idea but for Ether; that has $4.7 billion of Ether in the pot and=
 a 2.5% annual fee.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These trusts became a famous widowmaker trade =
in crypto; name any high-profile 2022 crypto bankruptcy, and you will proba=
bly find a reference to Grayscale in its bankruptcy filings. The situation =
is that early on (the Grayscale Bitcoin Trust was created in 2013), owning =
Bitcoin directly was a pretty off-putting proposition for a lot of people =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0you had to be fairly technically savvy to hold Bitcoin direc=
tly, or you had to own it on an exchange that would probably rob you or get=
 hacked =E2=80=94=C2=A0so owning shares in a pot of Bitcoin in your brokera=
ge account was pretty attractive. Ordinary investors who wanted Bitcoin exp=
osure without a lot of hassle wanted to buy Grayscale shares, so those shar=
es traded at a premium: If the pot had $12 of Bitcoin per share, the shares=
 might trade at $15.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So big crypto trading firms like Three Arrows =
Capital and Alameda Research would do the Grayscale arbitrage trade: You bu=
y $12 million of Bitcoin, you deliver it to Grayscale, you get back 1 milli=
on shares of the Grayscale Bitcoin Trust and you sell them for $15 million,=
 collecting the premium. It wasn=E2=80=99t quite as easy as that, though; f=
or securities-law reasons, you had to wait a while (originally a year, more=
 recently six months) between when you got the shares and when you sold the=
m. If the price of Bitcoin went down in that time, you=E2=80=99d lose money=
. An alternative trade=C2=A0was to=C2=A0<em>borrow=C2=A0</em>$12 million of=
 Bitcoin, deliver them to Grayscale, get shares, wait and sell them.=C2=A0T=
hen you had no exposure to Bitcoin prices; if the price of Bitcoin fell by =
50%, then you=E2=80=99d only get $7.5 million for your Grayscale shares but=
 you=E2=80=99d only have to pay $6 million to buy back the Bitcoins you bor=
rowed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the arbitrage firms <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30759013.257411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMDUvY3J5cHRvLWhhZC1hLWNyZWRpdC1i=
dWJibGU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMwNzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzA3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3fdb97ce" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  did this trade as a very=C2=A0<=
em>levered=C2=A0</em>bet</a>, borrowing a bunch of dollars or Bitcoins to d=
o the trade and collect the Grayscale premium. The results were:=C2=A0</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">lots of Bitcoin got locked up in Grays=
cale=E2=80=99s pot;</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">lots of Graysc=
ale Bitcoin Trust shares were created;</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">lots of big crypto arbitrage firms had huge levered bets on the Graysc=
ale premium.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over time, it became easier for ordinary peopl=
e to hold Bitcoin in other ways. Crypto exchanges (mostly) became a bit saf=
er and less likely to rob you; crypto self-custody became a bit easier. Reg=
ular retail brokerages got into the crypto business. Bitcoin futures starte=
d trading on regular futures exchanges, and=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30759013.257411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMTUvYml0Y29pbi1ldGZzLWFyZS1hbG1vc3Q=
taGVyZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzA3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3=
VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMDcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB282840e5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Bitcoin futures exchange-traded f=
unds</a>=C2=A0were approved. The demand for Grayscale shares waned, but the=
 supply grew as all these arbitrage firms were doing the Grayscale trade. T=
he results were:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">By 2020, the Grayscale premium collaps=
ed and became negative: Now Grayscale Bitcoin Trust shares trade at a=C2=A0=
<em>discount=C2=A0</em>to the value of the Bitcoin in the pot;</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Three Arrows and Alameda, which had made lever=
ed bets on the premium,=C2=A0went bankrupt, as did lots of the platforms (F=
TX, Voyager, Celsius, etc.) that were lending them money or Bitcoins to do =
the trade<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>;</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">People stopped doing the Gra=
yscale arbitrage trade: Since Grayscale shares were now trading at a discou=
nt, there was no reason to give Grayscale Bitcoins to get back shares, and =
no one has done so for two years; but</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">The Bitcoins that were=C2=A0<em>already=C2=A0</em>in Grayscale=E2=80=99=
s pot =E2=80=94=C2=A0$14 billion at current prices =E2=80=94=C2=A0stayed th=
ere. No Bitcoins are coming in anymore, but none are going out either.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As of yesterday, the closing price of a <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30759013.257411/aHR0cHM6=
Ly9ncmF5c2NhbGUuY29tL3Byb2R1Y3RzL2dyYXlzY2FsZS1iaXRjb2luLXRydXN0Lw/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cC0d6af257" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Grayscale Bitcoin Trust share</a> was $=
11.77, versus a net asset value per share of $20.33, a discount of 42%. The=
 Ethereum Trust discount is 55%.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, to be fair to Grayscale:=C2=A0I said that=
 this product design =E2=80=94=C2=A0Bitcoins can come into the pot but neve=
r come out =E2=80=94=C2=A0is bad for customers but good for Grayscale, but =
in fact Grayscale doesn=E2=80=99t like this product design either. Grayscal=
e has been asking the US Securities and Exchange Commission for years to ap=
prove the conversion of the trust into an exchange-traded fund. If the trus=
t becomes an ETF, then it will have the same creation/redemption mechanics =
as most other ETFs: Arbitrageurs can hand Grayscale Bitcoins, get back shar=
es, and sell them immediately; or they can hand Grayscale shares, get back =
Bitcoins, and sell them. That should lead to a price for the shares that cl=
osely tracks the net asset value of the pot of Bitcoins: If the shares trad=
e at a premium, arbitrageurs will deliver Bitcoin and get shares to sell, b=
ut if they trade at a discount arbitrageurs will buy shares to deliver to g=
et back Bitcoin.=C2=A0At today=E2=80=99s prices, closing the discount=C2=A0=
would create about $6 billion of value in the Bitcoin trust and about $2.6 =
billion of value for the Ethereum one.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It might also lead to =E2=80=A6=C2=A0huge infl=
ows into the trust? Huge outflows? Could go either way? In its early years,=
 Grayscale got huge inflows because it was a better-than-the-alternatives w=
ay to hold crypto, but right now it seems like a pretty terrible way to hol=
d crypto, what with the discounts and the locked-up Bitcoin. If it became a=
n ETF, investors could more easily take their crypto out, and they might. B=
ut on the other hand if it became an ETF it would once again be a comparati=
vely=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>way to hold crypto, so investors might put mor=
e money in again. The general sense =E2=80=94=C2=A0at least in 2021 and pro=
bably even now =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that running a spot Bitcoin ETF would be a=
 lucrative business. Though if=C2=A0it does become an ETF, presumably Grays=
cale will have to cut fees; 2% (or 2.5%!) is pretty rich for an ETF annual =
fee, and would probably attract competitors.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Grayscale has been trying to convert the trust=
 to an ETF, but the SEC keeps saying no, for reasons that I do not find esp=
ecially compelling. Grayscale has sued the SEC to force approval =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30759013.257=
