ground-color: #ccc;">  the Bloomberg News headline today</a>, and really an=
ybody can speculate on Bitcoin=C2=A0<em>now=C2=A0</em>but approving an ETF =
would make it a bit more convenient:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CAllowing an ETF means any=
body with a brokerage account =E2=80=94 which is basically available to any=
body who can fog a mirror in the US =E2=80=94 can now speculate on Bitcoin,=
=E2=80=9D said James Angel, an associate finance professor at Georgetown Un=
iversity. Angel signed on to one of the amicus briefs in support of Graysca=
le.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t think that the requirements fo=
r opening an account at Coinbase are=C2=A0<em>vastly=C2=A0</em>higher than =
=E2=80=9Cfog a mirror=E2=80=9D but, sure, a little.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But even without converting the trust into an =
ETF, Grayscale=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>allow redemptions: It could let peo=
ple come to it with shares and give them back a proportional amount of the =
Bitcoins in the pot; it could let people hand in shares worth $11.77 and gi=
ve them back $20.33 worth of Bitcoin. It has not done this due to fairly te=
chnical securities-law concerns: <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/30759013.257411/aHR0cHM6Ly9sYXdibG9ncy51Yy5lZHUvc2xkL3RoZS1k=
