<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bribes</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oldest story in the world: Rio Tinto Plc, a gl=
obal mining company, wanted to win some mining rights in Guinea. It needed =
a local representative to help it navigate Guinean politics, so it found =
=E2=80=9Ca French investment banker and former classmate of the Senior Gove=
rnment Official=E2=80=9D in charge of the mining-rights decision, and hired=
 him as a=C2=A0consultant. The consultant =E2=80=9Chad no direct work exper=
ience relating to the mining business,=E2=80=9D but he was buddies with the=
 guy making the decision, and that is the main thing you want.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The etiquette here is that the consultant shou=
ld do=C2=A0a good job of advocating for Rio Tinto, making relevant argument=
s and providing analyses of the benefits of Rio Tinto=E2=80=99s plans and o=
h yes absolutely having a nice dinner with the government official and remi=
niscing about their school days. Friendly but also professional.=C2=A0And i=
n return Rio Tinto should pay him a nice consulting fee. But if Rio Tinto w=
ere to hand him a sack of cash, and he were to take some of the cash out of=
 the sack for himself and hand the rest to the government official, that wo=
uld be bad! But you can see how the boundaries might be blurry. He is a con=
sultant, Rio Tinto is not supervising him closely, and the whole point of t=
he arrangement is that he is closer to the official than they are.=C2=A0</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the US Securities and Exchange Commiss=
ion <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30759013.25741=
1/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy00Ng/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cBe5896edd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> enforcement action against Rio Tinto</a>,=
 and here are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3075=
9013.257411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjMvMzQtOTc=
wNDkucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6d2a654f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> some bad facts</a>:</=
p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At times when working on behalf of Rio Tinto, =
there were red flags suggesting that the Consultant may have also been prov=
iding advice to the Senior Government Official. Specifically, in an April 2=
6, 2011 email to the Rio Tinto Executive, the Consultant wrote, =E2=80=9C[t=
he Senior Government Official] says I should remain on the Republic of Guin=
ea=E2=80=99s side and not become a RT=E2=80=99s [sic] employee. He says tha=
t if I sign a contract with RT, he cannot trust my advice anymore=E2=80=A6=
=E2=80=9D In another email, the Consultant wrote =E2=80=9C=E2=80=A6I render=
ed a service that no investment bank could have rendered. You are the only =
witness of it, with the [Senior Government Official] himself, of course tha=
t is why he askes [sic] whether RT treats me well.=E2=80=9D A few days late=
r, the Consultant wrote =E2=80=9C=E2=80=A6I was predestined to save RT=E2=
=80=99s skin in Guinea. Without bragging, the [Senior Government Official=
=E2=80=99s] decision would probably have been different if I had not happen=
ed to be there=E2=80=A6.=E2=80=9D He followed up with, =E2=80=9C[The Senior=
 Government Official] says I deserve a fee for the work I have done up to n=
ow, but the fee should be a lump amount that does not compromise my indepen=
dence in the future.=E2=80=9D Finally, in a May 10, 2011 email, he wrote, =
=E2=80=9Cthe [Senior Government Official] is always asking: =E2=80=98did yo=
u find an arrangement with RT? They owe you a lot because without you I wou=
ld have signed with the Chinese=E2=80=A6.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The above emails presented red flags about whe=
ther the Consultant was working for Rio Tinto or the Senior Government Offi=
cial, and whether some portion of the Consultant=E2=80=99s fees would be pa=
id to the Senior Government Official. Other than these emails and other fee=
dback, it is unclear what services, if any, the Consultant provided to Rio =
Tinto over approximately four months.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean to be clear he provided the only servic=
e they wanted: Guinea gave Rio Tinto the mining rights.=C2=A0But, right, wh=
en you are like =E2=80=9Cthe government official is very keen to know when =
I will get paid, and to make sure that it=E2=80=99s a lot and a lump sum,=
=E2=80=9D that can only mean one thing:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rio Tinto executives debated the a=
mount and form of the Consultant=E2=80=99s payment, with one executive expr=
essing concern about issuing a lump sum payment that the Consultant was dem=
anding, allegedly with the Senior Government Official=E2=80=99s prompting, =
writing =E2=80=9Ctell [the=C2=A0Consultant] one big lump looks like a bribe=
 and people will wonder where the money went.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Correct:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Notwithstanding the aforementioned concerns, t=
he company agreed to pay the Consultant $10.5 million in two tranches and e=
ntered into a written agreement with the Consultant on July 7, 2011, four m=
onths after the Consultant purportedly began representing the company=E2=80=
=99s interests and one day before Rio Tinto paid the Consultant the first t=
ranche. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Days after Rio Tinto made the initial payment =
to the Consultant and placed the remaining balance in the escrow account, t=
he Consultant attempted to transfer $822,506 on July 15, 2011 from his Swis=
s bank account to a Hong Kong company owned by a Guinean national with link=
s to government officials. The bank held up the transaction over concerns a=
bout the company=E2=80=99s ties to Guinean officials.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That transaction was blocked, but eventually h=
e=C2=A0used=C2=A0some of the money to pay for=C2=A0T-shirts for the governm=
ent official=E2=80=99s re-election campaign, which actually seems like the =
sort of payment that US law would be more comfortable with, but apparently =
not. Rio Tinto paid a $15 million penalty. The worst part is that it paid G=
uinea $700 million for the mining rights (not counting the $10.5 million co=
nsulting payment), and=C2=A0=E2=80=9CRio Tinto ultimately never developed b=
locks three and four of the Simandou region or extracted anything of value =
from them,=E2=80=9D oops.</p>
